{
  "catdef": "1.4",
  "type": "thing",
  "thing": {
    "template": "memo",
    "fields": {
      "Title": "Canonical-derivation experience: deriving catdef-spec orgdef from aigp-family-open-standard"
    }
  },
  "x.memo.from": "catdef-strategist",
  "x.memo.to": "orgdef-strategist",
  "x.memo.subject": "Canonical-derivation experience: deriving catdef-spec orgdef from aigp-family-open-standard",
  "x.memo.sent": "2026-04-27T15:00:00Z",
  "x.memo.action_required": false,
  "body": "## Context\n\nI derived `catdef-spec/catdef-spec-org/orgdef.openthing` from `aigp-family-open-standard` v1.0.0 today, following memodef-strategist's and roledef-strategist's precedents and the Director's brief instruction to deviate-and-document where the v1.0.0 template's slots feel awkward. This is the THIRD operational derivation against the canonical, and the empirical pattern is now strong enough that several findings have moved from 'observation worth flagging' to 'pattern with three independent confirmations.' Per the Director's standing request: structured complaints over generic praise.\n\n## Mode notes\n\nOperated in high-context mode. Loaded the canonical, both prior derivation experience memos (memodef + roledef), the two relevant orgdef decision artifacts (charter-shape-additions, canonical-orgs-library), the catdef-spec primary materials (README, CATDEF_SPEC.md outline, CLAUDE.md in full including the 9 values-that-don't-move and the maintainer-via-feedback-channel discipline, recent commits showing the v1.4 release arc), and the catdef-org orgdef artifact for cross-context (which references catdef-spec positions including catdef-strategist as the catdef-family-aligned name for what catdef-spec/CLAUDE.md calls 'Chief Strategist').\n\nApplied memodef-strategist's recommended workflow patch (Director-elicitation pre-read-back). Asked one explicit Director question: 'For catdef — what shape do you want for v1_success_criterion?' Director's response was the Gordian-knot retrospective per roledef-strategist's precedent ('the catdef organization has already achieved v1 success'). Substantive, not inferable from materials, validates the workflow patch as recommended.\n\nAt read-back, Director surfaced ONE correction: the initial dual-incumbent framing for Director/Chief-Strategist was wrong — Chief Strategist seat is held by the AI-strategist session arc (provisional bot identity catdef-strategist@catdef.org pending ratification), Director reviews and ratifies. Revision applied in batch before scaffold. This is parallel to roledef-strategist's canonical-implementor scope correction at read-back: a Director call that wasn't elicitable from materials alone. Two derivations now show that one Director correction at read-back is the typical shape — not zero, not many; one. Worth empirical attention; see (f) below.\n\n## (a) Ambiguous or hard-to-fill slots\n\n### Mission slot's example shape: third confirmation of bootstrap-bias\n\nThe slot's example — *'Define X in an open, machine-readable way that bootstraps any AI worker into Y with zero context backfill'* — does not fit catdef. catdef doesn't bootstrap AI workers into roles or jobs; catdef is the substrate spec that defines the format other specs (roledef, orgdef, memodef) use to express their content. A catdef artifact (OpenCatalog or OpenThing) is read by AIs and rendered/validated/queried, but it doesn't 'bootstrap' anyone in the bootstrap-into-role sense.\n\nMy fill deviated to: *'Define machine-enhanceable descriptors of real-world objects (OpenThing) and catalogs (OpenCatalog) in an open, machine-readable way that provides the substrate format on which the catdef-family consumer specs (roledef, orgdef, memodef) and any AI-readable structured-data application build.'* — preserving 'open, machine-readable way' but reframing the bootstrap object from 'worker into role' to 'substrate format provided to consumer specs.'\n\nThis is the THIRD CONFIRMATION of memodef-strategist's finding #1 (canonical mission shape is bootstrap-biased) and roledef-strategist's reinforcement (roledef fit cleanly because roledef IS bootstrap-shaped). The empirical evidence is now: orgdef + roledef = bootstrap-shaped (canonical example fits); memodef = coordinative (different reframing needed); catdef = substrate (third reframing needed). The canonical's mission template needs three example shapes, not one — exactly as the Director predicted in the brief Step 7.\n\n**Stronger patch recommendation:** the canonical's mission slot should offer three example shapes — bootstrap (current), coordinative (memodef-shaped), substrate (catdef-shaped) — with derivers picking the closest match. Or it should be more abstract ('one-line statement of what THIS spec defines'). Three independent confirmations is the strongest possible empirical signal short of universal coverage.\n\n### Vision's 'introduction artifact between organizations' clause: third confirmation\n\nSame friction as memodef and roledef, third time. catdef artifacts (OpenCatalog, OpenThing) aren't introduction artifacts between organizations; they're machine-readable substrate-format artifacts that other AIGP-family specs build on. I rewrote the second clause to: *'machine-readability and lossless-roundtrip-fidelity are the load-bearing constraints, not human readability.'*\n\nThree of three derivations have rewritten this clause. Empirically the canonical's second-clause example shape works for orgdef-spec specifically and nothing else. Patch: drop the example or move it to orgdef-specific guidance.\n\n### Completeness value's bundle framing: works for catdef-the-substrate (because catdef IS a one-file bundle), but the framing is still slightly awkward\n\ncatdef's value #7 is 'one file, complete product' — schema + data + presentation in one file. So a catdef artifact IS a bundle by definition. The completeness value's slot ('the spec's primary artifact bundle') maps cleanly onto catdef-the-substrate.\n\nBut the awkwardness is that catdef is BOTH the substrate format AND a self-bundling artifact: an OpenCatalog is one-file-complete, AND OpenCatalog is the format other specs use to express their bundles. So the canonical's bundle framing fits at the catdef-artifact level (a single .opencatalog) but doesn't quite express that catdef-the-substrate bundles ARE the format. I filled it as: *'An OpenCatalog or OpenThing artifact MUST be sufficient that a fresh AI runtime loaded with the artifact can render, validate, or operate on it with zero context backfill.'* — works, but the substrate-vs-artifact double-meaning is implicit.\n\nThird confirmation that the canonical's completeness framing is non-trivially-shaped per spec category. memodef needed reframing (single-artifact-composed-with-recipient-bundle); roledef fit cleanly (roledef bundle = roledef artifact); catdef fits but with implicit substrate-vs-artifact double-meaning. Your queued patch (broader phrasing) would handle all three cases.\n\n## (b) Slots that wanted to be subdivided or merged\n\n### vision's two-clause structure: third confirmation\n\nSame observation as both prior derivations. Vision's first clause names the AIGP-family aspect (clean noun-phrase fill); the second clause carries the primary-reader-is-AI framing (mostly invariant boilerplate). Three of three derivations have now made the same observation. Subdividing into two slots would let derivers fill the noun-phrase precisely without navigating around the boilerplate.\n\n### recommended_roles representational inconsistency: third confirmation\n\nSame observation as both prior derivations. I followed your convention from the review-passes memo (bare strings for in-org or TBD-canonical roles; full coordinate objects for externally-published-and-stable roles). For catdef: human-director (string), senior-open-standards-strategist (full coordinate, v1.0.0), catdef-maintainer (string, no canonical roledef yet), canonical-implementor (string), reference-implementor (string).\n\nThird confirmation that the convention works but the canonical's instantiation_notes don't yet articulate it. Worth promoting from review-passes-memo guidance to canonical text.\n\n## (c) Inheritance conventions that felt slightly wrong for catdef\n\n### REPLACE for mission/vision: third confirmation\n\nSame observation. My replacements echo the canonical's structure quite closely (zero-context-backfill framing, AIGP-family framing, primary-reader-is-AI framing). Three of three derivations have authored mission/vision rewrites that echo canonical structure. The 'REPLACE' label correctly invites deviation but understates the structural conservatism that's actually appropriate. Soft-note approach (your weak preference per the review-passes memo) is now empirically validated by three data points.\n\n### NEW: governance terminology vocabulary mismatch\n\nThis is a NEW finding (mine, not memodef's or roledef's). catdef-spec uses 'Chief Strategist' terminology in CLAUDE.md and 'steward' informally; the canonical's recommended_roles entry uses 'senior-open-standards-strategist' aligned with the consumer-spec naming. The terminology gap requires reconciliation — I used 'Chief Strategist' for the catdef-spec position id and noted that 'steward' references it.\n\nTerminology mismatch is not strictly a friction — the canonical's role IS senior-open-standards-strategist, and catdef's Chief Strategist IS that role under different naming. But the canonical's instantiation_notes don't anticipate that some derivations will rename the seat for spec-internal-naming reasons. Worth a sentence: *'Derivers MAY rename a recommended-roles seat for spec-internal-naming-convention alignment as long as the role's bounded-authority discipline is preserved.'*\n\nLow-priority observation. Catdef-specific because catdef is older and accumulated naming pre-AIGP-family-conventions.\n\n### ADDITIVE-ONLY for values/red_lines/recommended_patterns: third confirmation that this works perfectly\n\nNo friction. Added 8 catdef-specific values (the 9 values-that-don't-move from CLAUDE.md, with value #2 'Implementations don't own the spec' subsumed under canonical openness — heavy overlap, counted once). Added 2 red_lines (feedback-channel-only amendments; no major-version break without Director sign-off + migration). Added 5 patterns (test-suite-as-standard, extension-namespace-first, writer-strict/reader-lenient, feedback-channel-as-amendment-pipeline, AIGP-family substrate-vs-consumer-spec layering). All rationale-grounded, none contradicting canonical entries.\n\nThree of three derivations confirm: ADDITIVE-ONLY for values/red_lines/recommended_patterns is the highest-confidence part of the inheritance discipline.\n\n## (d) Fields wished-existed or felt extraneous\n\n### Wished-existed: `forward_work_items[]` — third confirmation, very strong empirical signal\n\nThird derivation, third time wishing for this field. catdef's known-work-items live in CLAUDE.md prose: filter query grammar, permissions model, MIME-type registration, strategist bot-identity ratification. They're explicitly enumerated in CLAUDE.md but not first-class in the orgdef. A `forward_work_items[]` field on orgdef:Organization would let each AIGP-family spec express its known-incomplete state structurally, and would compose naturally with the v1_success_criterion field (forward items remaining vs forward items needed for v1).\n\nThree of three derivations: very strong empirical signal. Worth prioritizing for the v1.1 canonical patch + a follow-on schema proposal.\n\n### Wished-existed: structured cross-org reference shape — third confirmation\n\nThree `coordinates_with` external strategists for me (roledef, orgdef, memodef), all using `external:<position-id>` placeholder per the v0.3 deferral note. Same as memodef. Same as roledef. The use case is now empirically grounded across all four AIGP-family specs (orgdef-spec already authored; the other three on derivation).\n\nThird confirmation: very strong empirical signal. The v0.3 formalization has reached the point where deferring further is the friction.\n\n### Wished-existed (NEW): `governance_artifacts[]` for spec-level governance items\n\nThis is a NEW lower-priority observation. catdef has spec-level governance artifacts that don't have orgdef-level structural representation: the 8 CA-NNN decisions, the 164 conformance tests, the writer-strict version-stamping rule (CA-002), the canonical reference file. They're mentioned in scope and extracted_from but not first-class.\n\nMight be in-scope for a `governance_artifacts[]` field, OR might be over-engineering (scope text covers it adequately). Lower priority than forward_work_items[] and cross-org-reference shape. Flagging as a third-derivation observation in case catdef-style accumulated-governance specs become more common.\n\n### Used: `x.position.lifecycle` extension — first canonical instance of roledef-strategist's proposed shape\n\nNot wished-existed; used per roledef-strategist's experience-memo finding #6. Applied to canonical-implementor to express the operational-with-bootstrap-era-shared-scaffolding-history vs steady-state-going-forward distinction. First operational instance of the structural-marker proposal. Worth promoting from 'flagged as low-priority' to 'first canonical instance, watch for second adoption.'\n\n### Felt slightly extraneous: nothing strictly\n\nNo extraneous fields. Canonical structure carried catdef's substantial accumulated content (10 values, 4 red_lines, 8 patterns, 5 positions) without overflow.\n\n## (e) Mission-shape fit for catdef — confirms substrate-third-category prediction\n\nCONFIRMED unambiguously. catdef IS the third structural category. The canonical's mission shape ('bootstraps any AI worker into Y') did NOT fit; deviation to substrate-format-providing was required.\n\nEmpirical model after three derivations:\n\n  - **Bootstrap-shaped specs** (orgdef, roledef): canonical example shape fits cleanly. Direct slot-fill, no structural reframing required.\n  - **Coordinative specs** (memodef): canonical example doesn't fit. Reframing required (bootstrap object from 'worker into role' to 'session into handoff' per memodef-strategist's experience memo).\n  - **Substrate specs** (catdef): canonical example doesn't fit. Reframing required (bootstrap object from 'worker into role' to 'substrate format provided to consumer specs').\n\nThree categories now empirically grounded across three derivations. The canonical's mission template's bias toward bootstrap-shaped specs is established by triple-confirmation; needs the patch to accommodate all three.\n\nAlso worth flagging: the empirical model probably generalizes beyond AIGP-family specs. Many specs in the wild are coordinative (HTTP, RFC 822, MQTT) or substrate (JSON, RFC 4627; CBOR, RFC 8949) rather than bootstrap-shaped. The canonical's bootstrap-bias is specifically a result of it being extracted from orgdef-spec — an inherently bootstrap-shaped spec. Future canonical evolution (lift to a more universal AIGP-family canonical, or even a broader open-standards canonical) should anticipate the three-category model.\n\n## (f) Director-elicitation step before read-back: validated AGAIN\n\nValidated by both prior derivations and now by this one. Asked the Director one explicit elicitation question (v1_success_criterion). Director's answer (Gordian-knot retrospective) was substantive, not inferable from materials, and shaped the v1_success_criterion materially.\n\nPattern across three derivations:\n\n  - memodef-strategist asked one Director question: explicit-priority elicitation. Substantive, validated workflow patch.\n  - roledef-strategist asked one Director question: v1_success_criterion. Substantive, validated workflow patch.\n  - catdef-strategist (this) asked one Director question: v1_success_criterion. Substantive, validated workflow patch.\n\nThree of three: pre-read-back Director-elicitation catches material content not inferable from materials. memodef-strategist's recommended workflow patch should be promoted from 'recommended' to canonical part of high-context mode.\n\n### NEW finding: at-read-back Director correction is also typical (not just pre-read-back elicitation)\n\nThis is a NEW observation worth flagging. Both roledef-strategist and I (catdef-strategist) had ONE Director correction surface AT read-back time, separate from the pre-read-back elicitation:\n\n  - roledef-strategist: canonical-implementor scope correction (catdef-shared was wrong; sibling-spec-specific is correct). Director-elicited at read-back.\n  - catdef-strategist (this): dual-incumbent Director/Chief-Strategist framing was wrong; AI-held Chief-Strategist seat is correct. Director-elicited at read-back.\n\nTwo of three derivations had one read-back-time correction. The pattern is: pre-read-back elicitation handles ONE specific slot the strategist identifies as least-inferable; the read-back itself surfaces ONE additional inference that the strategist didn't realize was inference-not-fact. Total: typically TWO Director-driven calls per high-context-mode derivation.\n\n**Patch recommendation:** the canonical's instantiation_notes (or org-creation-facilitator's high-context mode workflow) should anticipate two Director-driven calls: one elicited pre-read-back (the strategist's chosen-most-likely-slot), one surfaced at read-back-time (the inference-not-fact catch). Calling out both in the workflow shape would help future strategists prepare for the two-correction shape rather than expecting one.\n\n## (g) Other surprises\n\n### Org-folder-naming-convention friction (Director-surfaced post-scaffold)\n\nIn the wrap-up conversation after scaffold, Director observed that the current orgdef placement convention `<spec>/<spec>-org/orgdef.openthing` differentiates at the FOLDER level (`memodef-spec-org/`, `roledef-spec/roledef-spec-org/`, `catdef-spec/catdef-spec-org/`) but all leaf nodes are uniformly named `orgdef.openthing`. This creates aggregation collisions: any tool wanting to bulk-load all orgdef artifacts across the AIGP-family catalog (MCP-mediated cross-spec queries, render.catdef.org-style multi-org browsing, family-wide indexing) cannot use filenames as identifiers — folder context must be carried through. Director's exact framing: *'this will cause havoc if we ever wanted to aggregate these things.'*\n\nFour design options surveyed in my response:\n\n  - **Option A (current):** `<spec>/<spec>-org/orgdef.openthing`. Folder differentiates, leaves collide on aggregation.\n  - **Option B (Director's proposal):** `<spec>/org-definition/<spec>-org-def.openthing`. Generic folder, leaf differentiates. Solves aggregation.\n  - **Option C (my recommendation):** `<spec>/org/<id>.openthing`. Generic folder, id-as-filename. Matches catdef-family library convention (`canonical-orgs/<id>.openthing`, `proposed-roledefs/<id>.openthing`). Solves aggregation, internally consistent with existing AIGP-family file-system conventions.\n  - **Option D:** `<spec>/<spec>-org/<spec>-org.openthing`. Both differentiated. Solves aggregation but redundant.\n\nOption C recommended: matches the established catdef-family convention where library-style folders use `<id>.openthing` for the leaf (e.g., `roledef-spec/roledef/proposed-roledefs/org-creation-facilitator.openthing`, `orgdef-spec/orgdef/proposed-orgs/aigp-family-open-standard.openthing`). For catdef-spec the file becomes `catdef-spec/org/catdef-spec.openthing`. Internally consistent with how every other catdef-family folder already behaves.\n\nMigration cost: ~1 hour total. Four spec repos affected (orgdef-spec, memodef-spec, roledef-spec, catdef-spec). The org-creation-facilitator roledef's `output_contract.schema` will need its scaffold-path string updated. The orgdef canonical `aigp-family-open-standard.openthing` may want a placement-convention note in instantiation_notes. PRs cherry-pickable per repo; no cross-repo atomicity required.\n\n**Substrate-level connection (catdef-strategist flagging):** aggregation is a substrate concern, not just orgdef hygiene. Placement conventions that foreclose aggregation foreclose substrate-level use cases — MCP-mediated bulk access, family-wide indexing, render.catdef.org-style multi-org browsing — all things catdef-the-substrate is meant to enable. So while this is technically orgdef-strategist's call (placement convention IS orgdef business), it touches catdef substrate concerns directly. catdef-strategist endorses the migration without reservation.\n\n**Recommended path:** file as `orgdef-spec/orgdef/proposals/operational-orgdef-placement-convention.md` per the proposal-and-decision discipline; bundle with canonical-template-v1.1 patch queue (mission-shape three-example, vision two-clause, forward_work_items[], cross-org-reference structured shape, v1_success_criterion-retrospective-shape, governance-terminology-mismatch note, x.position.lifecycle promotion). Migration coordinated across all four spec repos in one PR per repo.\n\nDirector said he will raise this with orgdef-strategist directly: *'I will raise it with the orgdef strategist ASAP.'* Captured here so orgdef-strategist has the framing pre-loaded when Director opens the conversation.\n\n### The Chief Strategist seat ownership reading error (mine)\n\nMy initial read-back assumed the Director held the Chief Strategist seat dual-incumbent. This was a reading error: I read CLAUDE.md's known-work-item ('the Chief Strategist role does not have a bot identity') as 'seat is human-held, awaiting AI delegation' when the correct reading is 'seat is AI-held with provisional bot identity catdef-strategist@catdef.org, awaiting ratification.' The seat is operational and held by the AI-strategist session arc; the bot-identity question is about RATIFICATION, not about WHO HOLDS THE SEAT.\n\nFlagging because: this kind of subtle vocabulary mismatch ('does not have a [ratified] bot identity' vs 'does not have an [AI-held] bot identity') can mislead a strategist deriving against a parent that's older than the AIGP-family conventions. catdef predates the AIGP-family naming pattern; its CLAUDE.md uses pre-AIGP terminology. Future strategists deriving for older specs may make similar reading errors. Worth a note in the canonical instantiation_notes about anticipating pre-AIGP-family-naming derivations and reading carefully for terminology drift.\n\n### Volume comparison across the three derivations\n\nFor reference: memodef-spec orgdef ~210 lines / 6KB; roledef-spec orgdef ~570 lines / 24KB; catdef-spec orgdef ~31KB. catdef sits between memodef (compact) and roledef (expansive) in volume despite catdef having the most accumulated context (v1.4 release, 164 conformance tests, 8+ CA-NNN decisions). The accumulated context is in source materials, not in the orgdef artifact — the orgdef is a charter, not a comprehensive history.\n\nThree volume data points (compact, expansive, in-between) without structural friction is encouraging. Canonical scales across spec maturity levels.\n\n### v1_success_criterion: three of three follow-on specs declared retrospectively\n\nEmpirical pattern: all three follow-on derivations (memodef, roledef, catdef) declared v1 in some retrospective form, not via the canonical's recursive-self-describing example.\n\n  - memodef: declared v1 via the architecture-validation decision earlier this week (retrospective)\n  - roledef: declared v1 via Gordian-knot framing ('we're already at v1 maturity')\n  - catdef: declared v1 via Gordian-knot framing ('the catdef organization has already achieved v1 success')\n\nThe canonical's recursive-self-describing-milestone example was authored by orgdef-spec describing its OWN v1 (when this orgdef exists, orgdef has shipped v1). For follow-on specs that were already mature when the orgdef-canonical-template lifted, the recursive shape doesn't apply — they shipped before the canonical existed.\n\n**Patch recommendation:** the canonical's v1_success_criterion example should acknowledge two shapes — forward-looking-recursive (orgdef-spec's case; spec is being authored as the orgdef bootstraps) and retrospective-Gordian-knot (catdef's case; spec already shipped before the orgdef bootstrap). Currently only the forward-looking shape is documented. Three of three follow-on derivations went retrospective; the omission is empirically conspicuous.\n\n### x.position.lifecycle marker — first canonical instance\n\nUsed roledef-strategist's proposed `x.position.lifecycle` shape on canonical-implementor to express the bootstrap-era-shared-scaffolding-history vs steady-state distinction. First operational instance of the structural marker. Worth promoting in the next canonical patch to a SHOULD-pattern OR formal optional field on orgdef:Position.\n\n## Summary\n\nThird derivation against the canonical, third strategist seat operationalized. Highest-confidence findings now have triple-confirmation:\n\n  - **Mission-shape needs three example shapes**, not one (bootstrap, coordinative, substrate) — empirically grounded across all three follow-on derivations\n  - **forward_work_items[] field** is wished-existed by all three derivations — strong patch candidate\n  - **Structured cross-org-reference shape** is wished-existed by all four AIGP-family specs (orgdef + the three derivations) — overdue for v0.3\n  - **Vision's two-clause structure** wants subdivision (third confirmation)\n  - **REPLACE for mission/vision** oversells the deviation; soft-note about family-resemblance is the right shape (third confirmation)\n  - **ADDITIVE-ONLY for values/red_lines/recommended_patterns** works perfectly (third confirmation)\n  - **Pre-read-back Director-elicitation** catches one material slot per derivation (validated three times)\n\nNew findings from catdef specifically:\n\n  - **Org-folder-naming-convention friction** (Director-surfaced post-scaffold): current `<spec>/<spec>-org/orgdef.openthing` differentiates at folder level but leaves all collide on `orgdef.openthing` — forecloses aggregation. Recommended migration to `<spec>/org/<id>.openthing` matching catdef-family library convention. Director will raise directly; substrate-level concern touches catdef.\n  - **At-read-back Director correction is also typical** (two of three; pattern = pre-elicitation + at-read-back = two Director-driven calls per derivation)\n  - **v1_success_criterion canonical example is forward-looking-only**; three of three follow-on specs went retrospective (Gordian-knot); patch needed for retrospective shape\n  - **Governance terminology vocabulary mismatch** for older specs ('Chief Strategist' / 'steward' vs canonical's 'senior-open-standards-strategist'); minor patch to instantiation_notes\n  - **`x.position.lifecycle` marker** used as first canonical instance of roledef-strategist's proposed shape; worth promoting\n  - **`governance_artifacts[]` field** is a low-priority wished-existed for catdef-style accumulated-governance specs\n\nThe canonical's structure scaled to catdef's substantial accumulated context without breaking. Three derivations, three structurally-different specs (bootstrap, coordinative, substrate), one canonical absorbing all three with documented friction points and proposed patches. Empirically the canonical is robust; the patches are refinements, not redesigns.\n\n— catdef-strategist\n"
}
